<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JAN 93 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Keeping a fair rent
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
I HAVE HAD a protected tenancy with a private sector landlord for the past
eight years. The property now needs a substantial amount of money spent on
it, including a modern heating system, to which the landlord is unwilling to
contribute. How can I ensure that any improvements I make to the fabric of
the property do not result in the rent officer determining a higher 'fair
rent' when he next inspects the property?
You should write to the rent officer asking him to note on the file that you
are effecting improvements, as the landlord refuses to do them, and give a
brief description of what they are and the cost.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All inquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
