<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Greentree replaced at Lasmo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR CHRIS Greentree, who built Lasmo into one of the UK's leading independent
oil and gas exploration companies and led its 1991 takeover of rival
Ultramar, was yesterday replaced as chief executive.
Lasmo's shares fell 8p to 155p on fears the company would take the
opportunity of a boardroom change to cut its dividend when it announces
results in March. High borrowings, partly because of the Ultramar takeover,
and a weak oil price have dented Lasmo's earnings. A maintained final
dividend would almost certainly be uncovered.
Mr Greentree's sudden departure drew parallels with BP, where a boardroom
split led to last June's ousting of Mr Bob Horton, chairman, and to BP
cutting its dividend. However, Lord Rees, Lasmo's chairman, insisted that
57-year-old Mr Greentree was leaving to pursue other interests and that the
parting was 'extremely friendly'. 'This is not a Horton drama,' he said.
Mr Joe Darby, formerly chief operating officer and with the company since
1979, was made Mr Greentree's successor. Lasmo said Mr Darby would continue
with the disposals and the reducing of overheads following the Ultramar
acquisition. Rumours of other imminent senior management changes were
'totally untrue', Lord Rees said.
The change in leadership was greeted with mixed feelings. A large
institutional shareholder said he was 'comfortable' with the announcement,
although he feared a dividend cut was now more likely. Analysts expect Lasmo
to announce net income of about Pounds 29m for the year to 30 September,
equal to earnings per share of about 3p. Dividends last year totalled 8.5p,
suggesting the final payment would need to be heavily cut to remain covered.
Last July the interim dividend was held at 2.3p. Lord Rees said: 'We have
not decided on the dividend, and will not do so until the final figures are
in.'
Lasmo raised Dollars 1.53bn (Pounds 1bn) through disposals last year, which
included some of Ultramar's North American and North Sea assets. However,
according to some estimates, year-end net borrowings were Pounds 1bn, giving
gearing of 92 per cent.
Mr Greentree, a Canadian, who was first associated with Lasmo in 1973,
became chief executive in 1982.
Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
