<TEXT>
EUROPEAN airlines said yesterday the number of passengers they carried on
international routes rose by 12 per cent last year, but the increase largely
represented recovery of traffic lost during 1991, Reuter reports from
Brussels.
The Association of European Airlines said its 23 members carried 110m
passengers over the year, 11.7m up on 1991 when traffic was hit by the Gulf
war which persuaded many prospective passengers to stay at home.
The AEA also forecast gloomy financial results for its members last year.
