<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Pledge given over unification of
VAT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR John Cope, paymaster-general, assured the Commons last night that the
government was not 'wedded' to the unification of taxation rates across the
European Community, Ivor Owen writes.
He was seeking to allay fears about the provisions in the Maastricht treaty
dealing with the harmonisation of indirect taxes during further debate on
the European Communities (Amendment) Bill.
Sir John urged critics of the treaty not to confuse harmonisation and
unison. He said 'harmony involves different notes which blend with one and
other to create a pleasing overall sound'. Harmonisation did not mean that
every member state had to have exactly the same tax system or rates.
</TEXT>
