<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: MPs and fraud office in Maxwell
deadlock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Serious Fraud Office and the Commons social security committee failed to
reach agreement last night on how to proceed with planned public hearings
into the theft of funds from Maxwell company pension schemes.
The SFO requested earlier this week that hearings arranged by the committee
be called off because some of those due to appear at them could be material
witnesses in criminal proceedings.
The SFO had argued that disclosure of some information could lead defendants
to argue that they had been denied the opportunity of a fair trial.
In a two-hour meeting late yesterday, MPs on the committee put five options
to the SFO for dealing with the hearings. They expect to receive their
response in time to take a final decision the week after next. One option is
to hold all the hearings in private.
The MPs told the SFO that some of their forthcoming hearings will not be
affected by the SFO's concerns. They emphasise that the decision about how
to handle the hearings will ultimately be for them rather than the SFO. The
SFO's views will be taken into account, though.
</TEXT>
