<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Costs threaten 'free' banking: Current account charges may
be reinstated to pay Pounds 4.5bn clearing bill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS have moved a step closer to the reintroduction of charges on personal
customers' accounts with the discovery that the cash and cheque clearing
system is costing them Pounds 4.5bn a year.
The figure was worked out by the Association for Payment Clearing Services
during an industry-wide review started by the banks last year. It is the
first time the banks have managed to quantify the cost of clearing.
In the past, the clearing system was subsidised by banks earning interest on
customers' funds, but banks are now considering reintroducing charges, even
on personal accounts that are in credit, in order to cover their overheads.
Since late 1985, the big four English clearing banks have all provided free
banking to customers who keep their current accounts in credit. Other banks,
including Co-operative Bank and Scottish banks, had already followed the
same policy.
The study of clearing costs will also give added impetus to banks' efforts
to cut the number of branches and staff. Cost reduction is one component of
attempts to raise operating profits to compensate for lending losses in the
1980s.
Three cheque and credit clearing companies operate different types of
clearing services under Apacs. Some 21 banks participate directly in these
operating companies, while hundreds of other institutions have access to
clearing through them.
The Pounds 4.5bn figure is disclosed in Apacs' annual report, which also
says that banks and building societies contained the rise in credit card
fraud to 10 per cent in 1992. They lost Pounds 165.6m to fraud in 1991, up
35 per cent on 1990.
The volume and value of lower-value cheques passing through the clearing
system in 1992 fell for the second year running after many years of growth.
The value of cleared cheques fell 3 per cent to Pounds 4.18bn a day, and
volume fell 4 per cent to 8.6m.
The volume of transactions passing through the banks' Bacs system for bulk
electronic clearing rose by 7 per cent to Pounds 1.8bn, while there was a 12
per cent rise in volume in the Chaps system for high-value credit clearing.
The Apacs review is still under way, and banks will decide on strategies
after receiving the full results. Mr Dick Allen, Apacs chief executive, says
in the Apacs annual report that cost reduction 'is a high priority'. The
banks started the review to take account of changes in banking services
including the growth of telephone banking.
</TEXT>
