<DATE>930129
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Survey of Personal Equity Plans (23): All in one basket, or
pick your own - Self-Select &amp; Single-Company PEPs / Two variations that may
appeal to the investor who has time and knowledge - as well as the
willingness to accept greater risk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SELF-SELECT and single-company personal equity plans are the lesser
principalities within the Pep empire.
Neither has been as popular as managed and trust-based Peps, but both can
stake a claim to a place in an investor's portfolio.
Single company Peps were launched at the beginning of 1991, with the main
aim of allowing employees in an approved share-option scheme to transfer
their shares to a Pep once the shares emerged from the scheme. The transfer
can be made directly, without the usual 'bed and breakfasting' arrangement
and without any liability for capital gains tax, so long as the transfer is
made within 90 days.
Individuals are allowed to invest Pounds 3,000 a year in a single-company
Pep a year, in addition to the Pounds 6,000 general Pep limit. Over 110,000
single-company plans were taken out in 1991, and the amount invested was
Pounds 270m, according to figures from the Inland Revenue. This represents
only 5 per cent of the total Pep market by number of plans, and just over 4
per cent of the market by value.
The main drawback with single-company Peps for the general investor is the
risk resulting from lack of diversification. If you put the whole of your
Pep investment in one share, you risk that company collapsing. A general Pep
allows you to increase diversification over the years - by putting in Pounds
6,000 a year for 5 years, for example, you would be able to get a fair
degree of diversification.
You can, of course, take out a different single-company Pep each year. They
are also very useful for those who have already accumulated a substantial
portfolio of shares and want to hold as much as possible in a tax-efficient
form.
Beginner investors, however, should only consider a single-company Pep if
they have already used up the maximum in a general Pep.
Single-company Peps can be managed by a Pep plan manager, but are more
popular on a self-select basis. John Spiers, of BESt Investment, says that
most single-company plans are self-select, because it is difficult for
investors to justify the difference in cost with a managed Pep when the
investment dilemma is restricted to choosing a single stock.
For many people, the most suitable companies are likely to be those which
offer a good yield and are able to maintain their dividend.
An even cheaper way of taking out a single-company Pep is through a Pep
provider whose costs are subsidised by the company itself. Many FT-SE 100
companies provide this service, to reward their existing their small
investors and to encourage new ones.
The main Pep providers who specialise in this field are Bradford &amp; Bingley,
Hoare Govett, NatWest stockbrokers and Cazenove. CCC&amp;P, which also used to
be heavily involved in corporate Peps, closed this part of its business in
October, recommending companies to transfer instead to Henderson
Administration.
The drawback with obtaining a Pep in this way - for example, an ICI Pep
through its sponsors, Hoare Govett - is that you cannot then switch another
company's shares into the plan, if your view of ICI's prospects changes.
Self-select Peps are general Peps, subject to the usual Pounds 6,000 per
year maximum; but, as their name suggests, the stock is chosen by the
investor rather than a plan manager.
Clearly, self-select Peps will only appeal to those with the time and the
knowledge to manage their own portfolio. Investors will still have to
operate through a plan manager, because only they are authorised to run
Peps.
Roz Barder, editor of Chase de Vere's Pepguide, says that out of the 700
schemes listed in the guide, only 75 are self-select. Your choice of Pep
plan manager is therefore more limited, but that can make the task easier.
The important criteria for making a choice will be the size and structure of
charges, efficiency of service and administration, and any restrictions or
conditions imposed on the Pep by its plan managers.
Some plan managers structure their charge on the self-select Pep in a way to
discourage frequent dealing. Others may have cheaper dealing charges but
higher management or initial charges. Some will have both high dealing and
management charges, and should therefore be avoided.
BESt Personal Equity Plan has calculated total charges on a self-select Pep
as a percentage cost of the investment. The calculation assumes that the
full amount was put in when the plan was taken out, and that the average
investor changed his portfolio twice during a three-year period.
The average cost for the average investor is 13.3 per cent on these
assumptions. Mr Spiers says that two of the cheapest providers are Alliance
Trust and Lloyds Bank, with 1.8 per cent and 4.9 per cent respectively.
There are restrictions, however. Alliance Trust requires you to deposit the
first Pounds 1,500 in one of its investment trusts, while Lloyds Bank, with
its very low brokerage commission of 0.2 per cent, only deals on a certain
day each month and restricts the choice of stock to a list of 100 blue-chip
companies.
Many of the plan managers charge a management fee for self-select Peps,
which may appear incongruous because it is the investor who is managing the
Pep by selecting stock and deciding when to buy or sell. However, Ms Barder
says that companies without a management charge will probably impose a fee
for dividend collection instead. She also advises investors to watch out for
exit penalties.
If you are going to be a relatively inactive investor, a self-select Pep
should work out to be much cheaper than a managed Pep, but frequent dealing
will raise the costs. If you are an active investor, it is probably better
to take out a self-select Pep with a stockbroker, because dealing can be
done immediately, rather than at the end of the day or at certain points in
the month, which is a system that many of the banks operate.
Consider, too, whether there are restrictions on the number of stocks that
can be held in the Pep, and whether you have the flexibility to choose any
stock you like, including an investment or unit trust. Some plan managers
will provide advice, despite the Pep's being self-select, but this is likely
to be when you already have an existing portfolio with them.
</TEXT>
