<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Financial Times Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (17):
The high-growth tax saver that turned to catastrophe - Hindsight / Brenda
Vernelle wanted to top up her savings as she approached retirement, so she
bought a maximum investment plan. However, the advantages that she had been
led to expect quickly evaporated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABOUT THIS time every year, financial salesmen unleash their most effective
weapon - the 'buy now while stocks last' argument.
The end of the tax year is helpful to them; but also, every budget is
preceded by speculation that some tax loophole or by speculation thatn some
tax loophole or by speculation than some tax loophole or another is about to
be closed.
In the haste that surrounds these occasions, many investors find themselves
with inappropriate products. This is not surprising - if the tax loophole
was worth exploiting in the first place, investors would have considered it
already.
But it can be worse. Sometimes, in haste, the client does not even get the
tax advantages.
This was the story for Brenda Vernelle, a polytechnic lecturer from
Huddersfield, Yorkshire, who was sold a Save &amp; Prosper maximum investment
plan (Mip) in the spring of 1984.
A Mip is a life assurance plan, which lasts a minimum of 10 years. The
amount of life cover bought with premiums is kept to a minimum, while the
maximum allowable goes towards investment. Thus it is effectively just a
savings plan, which brings limited life cover tagging along.
The spring of 1984 was when life assurance premium relief was removed in the
budget. Until then, tax relief was available on premiums paid into the plan,
which then went on to produce tax-free pay-outs from a relatively
tax-efficient fund. That tax relief was stopped, except for policies already
in force.
There had been much speculation that such a move was in the pipeline, and so
Ms Vernelle, who wanted to step up her savings as she approached retirement,
was persuaded to open a Mip.
She submitted her forms, and paid her first premiums, in April 1984, before
the tax changes came into effect.
But there was a problem. She said: 'There was a muddle over getting the
doctor's report on it initially, and by the time this came, even though I
had already paid three months on it, new legislation had been implemented,
and I lost tax relief on it anyway.'
This more or less destroyed the point of taking out the plan. However, Ms
Vernelle decided to carry on, under pressure from her salesman, who left the
company shortly afterwards.
Before taking it out, she had also asked for confirmation that the 10-year
limit was not binding. At that point, she wanted to retire at the age of 62,
an age she attained this year, which meant that she would ideally need to
surrender it after 7 1/2 years.
She was assured that she could do this without tax penalty, and that any
penalty for early encashment would be trivial.
In the event, she wanted to cash it in after seven years, in April 1991. By
this time she had paid in total premiums of Pounds 8,400. The total she
received as a pay-out was Pounds 8,725.81.
As she wryly pointed out, there was no problem with paying tax on this sum]
Total charges for early discontinuance of the policy had taken a bite of
Pounds 459.24 - rather more than her salesman had led her to believe.
For what was supposed to be a tax-efficient high-growth investment to boost
her retirement savings, the investment had proved to be 'catastrophic'. Base
rates stood at 14 per cent at the time she took the cash, and building
societies had consistently offered basic-rate taxpayers returns above the
rate of inflation throughout the period of her investment. The Mip had not
even come close to beating inflation.
With hindsight, it is easy to see how it happened. Mips rely on unit-linked
investments, and can switch between a variety of funds. This is an
attractive feature, particularly when the provider has as large a range of
funds as Save &amp; Prosper, because it allows investors to 'play the market'
and catch the areas of best growth at any time.
But it also makes mistakes easy. And after four years of mediocre
performance - in the wake of the Black Monday crash in October 1987 - April
1991 was not a good time to take the profits from a unit-linked investment.
On the advice of various different salesmen, Ms Vernelle's Mip switched from
the Global Equity fund, which had been doing well, to the Special Situations
fund in April 1988. This was a bad time to move into a speculative fund, and
it lost money. There was a later switch into European Growth, which also
lost money.
Other choices of fund could have delivered a better pay-out, but the advice
was not there. Eventually, having taken retirement earlier than she had
planned, she was advised to cut her losses and encash the policy - another
move which hindsight suggests would have been a mistake, as the market has
picked up in the past 18 months.
Ms Vernelle reported the case to the Consumers' Association, for its Worst
Buys of the Year study. Somewhat alarmingly, it was not the worst. This is
because this kind of case is all too common - many other people close to
retirement have been rushed into investments for tax reasons, and done
badly.
Jean Eaglesham, of the Consumers' Association, draws several conclusions
from the affair: 'One lesson is to try always to get the salesman's
recommendation in writing, and push them as hard as you can for the
conditions of their recommendations. If there's a good reason to go into it,
get that in writing if at all possible. Get any recommendation to be as
detailed as possible, and don't be frightened to go back to them.'
Such a 'reason why' letter from an adviser will become a legal requirement
if the new rules on disclosure advocated by the Securities and Investments
Board are adopted. The requirement seems to be overdue, as the CA has had
many cases of people who had relied on verbal recommendations, and could not
pin the company down for compensation when the advice turned out to be
wrong.
Fortunately, in this case there was a happy ending. After being contacted by
the FT, Mr Colin Rye, of Save &amp; Prosper's insurance division, said the
circumstances made it sufficiently clear that Ms Vernelle was planning to
surrender early that he was prepared to make an ex gratia refund of her
discontinuance charges, even though there was nothing in writing to prove
what she had been told. Ms Vernelle was very pleased about this, as it
belatedly makes up for one of her greatest problems with the product.
Ms Eaglesham adds: 'Don't assume that the salesmen are acting in your best
interest. It is worth going to them on the assumption that they are working
for themselves.'
Ms Vernelle's ultimate complaint, as she contemplates retirement on these
low savings, is that the full risks were never made clear. She says: 'I do
think that something which is as chancy as that is not a marvellous way of
saving for your future. Ten years ahead, it's a terrible gamble if your
savings depend on the value of the market on one particular day.'
</TEXT>
