<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Financial Times Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (11):
Nordic devaluations are balanced by strong stock market gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TURMOIL IN the currency markets was the greatest influence on European
equity markets in the final quarter of 1992, but the countries forced to
devalue their currencies were consoled with the best-performing stock
markets.
According to the FT-A World Indices, Finland, which decided to let the
markka float in September, made the greatest gain in the quarter: 37.1 per
cent in local currency terms. Sweden, which followed Finland's lead in
November, came second with a rise of 33.4 per cent, and Italy came third
with a rise of 26.9 per cent. The gains in Finland and Sweden helped to
propel the Nordic index 21.9 per cent higher, compared with a gain of only
10.1 per cent for the whole of Europe.
Stock market analysts were not surprised by the extent of the gains,
triggered by the various currency devaluations, which in general led to an
improvement in the international competitiveness of countries whose
currencies have been devalued. In particular, Sweden is seen as a major
beneficiary of devaluation, because of its many international companies,
which have undergone extensive restructuring over the past two years.
However, Hoare Govett has advised clients to avoid Swedish companies with
the highest exposure to Germany, where the economy is expected to slow this
year, and concentrate instead on US-sensitive and cyclical stocks.
Towards the end of the year, continental markets were lifted by traditional
year-end rallies, fuelled by hopes of a recovery in the US economy and of a
cut in interest rates in Germany early in 1993. However, analysts warned at
the time that these hopes must be countered by signs of deteriorating
earnings growth on the continent and danger signals from Germany about its
economy.
Fear of economic recession, and profit warnings from the corporate sector,
contributed to the lacklustre performance of the German market in the final
quarter. It rose only 4.2 per cent in local currency terms. During the whole
year it lost 5.3 per cent but, in sterling terms, it rose 9.6 per cent, due
to the strength of the Deutsche Mark and the pound's weakness.
Kleinwort Benson underweighted Germany in its recommended asset allocation
for 1993, given what it called the appalling outlook for earnings. In its
view, both macro forecasts for the economy and micro forecasts for
individual companies were still far too high. Furthermore, the longer the
Bundesbank kept interest rates high, the harder the inevitable revaluation
of the D-Mark would hit the earnings outlook.
France, on the other hand, should be the main beneficiary if the Bundesbank
cuts interest rates, because this would take pressure off the franc and pave
the way for lower interest rates in France. Hoare Govett recommended an
overweight position in French equities for 1993, given its above-average GDP
growth (1.5 per cent in 1993, compared with 1.2 per cent for the
Netherlands, 1.0 per cent for Spain, 0.8 per cent for Switzerland and a fall
of 0.8 per cent in Germany) and low inflation.
Switzerland, the best performer in Europe in 1992 with a rise of 21.8 per
cent in local currency terms, is also expected to do well in 1993. In
December, Goldman Sachs believed there was scope for an earnings
growth-driven rise in the Swiss index of between 12 and 13 per cent over the
coming 10-to-14 months, and that equities should outperform both bonds and
cash.
Strategists at SG Warburg offered some words of caution regarding
continental European equities in 1993, which they believed would be largely
held back by deteriorating earnings growth prospects. 'We believe that
earnings momentum, rather than interest rates, holds the key to performance
in Europe (historically this has certainly been the case),' the broker said
in its 1993 asset allocation outlook.
</TEXT>
