<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Financial Times Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (10):
London puts optimism on hold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALTHOUGH ECONOMIC recession still hung over the Christmas festivities,
equity market indices stood at record levels on New Year's Eve, with UK
stocks having outperformed against both the rest of Europe and the rest of
the world.
Share prices rose sharply in significantly increased trading volume as fund
managers took in the full implications of sterling's somewhat hasty
departure from the ERM network in mid-September. By the end of the year, the
pound had been devalued by nearly 5 per cent on the sterling exchange rate
index, offering a powerful boost to export sales prospects.
In November, the autumn economic statement from Mr Norman Lamont, chancellor
of the exchequer, put some teeth into the government's stated policy of
re-stimulating economic growth. Domestic interest rates were cut by one
point to 7 per cent, and there were measures to help car sales and the
battered homebuilding sector.
Investors responded readily, setting aside doubts about sterling's prospects
outside the ERM or, indeed, the wider question of whether either the UK or
other leading world economies could be rescued from recession so easily.
All equity sectors showed positive returns over the final quarter, noted
NatWest Securities - even the badly-battered building sectors, which brushed
aside their setbacks in the previous quarter.
Investors hastened to switch portfolios into the cyclical stocks likely to
lead the way into recovery (motors, hotels and leisure, and food
manufacturers), and out of the defensive stocks into which they had flocked
in the third quarter (pharmaceuticals, utilities, and selected financials).
Faith in a consumer-led recovery revived, and store and other retail issues
began to anticipate a good Christmas trade. Even the sorely-hurt property
sector turned in a return of 19.3 per cent, against minus 12.9 in the
preceding three months.
Investors in the UK market also took a benign view of developments
elsewhere. Signs of recovery in the US economy were eagerly received in
London. From their new position outside the ERM, UK investors saw pressures
on other member currencies - in particular, the French franc  - as a further
indication that Britain had merely anticipated moves to lower interest rates
across Europe. By the year-end, London was convinced that a cut in German
rates was not far away.
A final flourish of optimism in December took market indices to new peaks,
leaving the FT-SE All-Share Index with a total return of 14 per cent on the
quarter. This outstripped the 12.7 per cent return on the narrower FT-SE 100
Share Index, as investors moved towards the second-tier issues where
potential gains are greater when the economy recovers.
The move towards smaller stocks remained a feature as the market moved into
the new year, when the FT-SE Mid 250 Index reached new peaks, although the
FT-SE 100 was slipping back.
These trends must be measured against a substantial increase in retail
trading in equities - retail business is the genuine outside customer
interest. Retail business averaged more than Pounds 1bn daily during the
final quarter, indicating a return to profitable trading levels for the
London securities industry as well as a convincing level of investment in
equities.
Confidence remained high as the final quarter of 1992 passed into history,
although many strategists warned that the market had run too far in
December, and that equity valuations of around 17 times historic earnings
were probably too high. In the short term, equities can expect a further
one-point cut in UK base rates, but this will probably be the last rate cut
in this cycle.
Economic recovery could still prove elusive, and inflation the more likely
reality. Equities face pressure both from government funding and from
looming rights issues. And there are already fears that Mr Lamont's budget,
due in March, may bring higher taxes.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
