<PROFILE>_AN-DA4ASAFBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930129
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Financial Times Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (30):
Postscript
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EQUITIES HAVE started to show their attractions again. The table indicates
that many of those investors who opted for unit and investment trusts in
1992 did better than those who stuck with the building society.
Over the year, the average gain among the international investment trusts,
for example, was 22.3 per cent. That gain was helped by sterling's dramatic
depreciation after Black Wednesday.
But even in Britain, the average UK general unit trust rose 11.1 per cent.
That return is effectively net, because basic-rate tax is deducted at source
from dividends and few investors pay capital gains tax. Building society
investors will have done well to earn more than about 7 per cent net over
the entire year (based on Halifax BS figures).
Glancing at the tables, 11 of the 14 unit trust sectors would have beaten
the building society return, as would 10 of the 13 investment trust sectors.
And looking back five years, any investors who were bold enough to buy
trusts in January 1988 (right after the crash) will have made some very
healthy profits: Pounds 1,000 invested in Foreign &amp; Colonial, the largest
investment trust, would have turned into Pounds 2,559; the same sum in the
Newton Income unit trust would have become Pounds 2,003.
The biggest gains were obtainable in the Far Eastern markets. Oriental
investment trusts which exclude Japan have shown an average rise of 44 per
cent over one year and 186 per cent over five; among unit trusts, the
equivalent figures are 36 per cent and 181 per cent.
Whether investors will be lured into buying trusts by these performance
figures is a difficult question. Many will have bad memories of having
bought at the top of the market in 1987, and may be cautious about buying
into equities at a time when the UK stock market is hovering around an
all-time high (in nominal terms, at least).
On the other hand, with returns on building societies now down to meagre
levels, a higher-rate taxpayer can enjoy a better income from some unit and
investment trust Peps than from cash. In the US, low interest rates have
caused many investors to switch from cash to shares; perhaps their
transatlantic cousins will follow suit.
Those who like 'bottom-fishing' may be lured by the disappointing returns
achieved in the smaller companies sector, where investor hopes were high in
1987. Smaller company shares underperformed in each of the years 1989-92.
Some day they will recover, and unit and investment trusts will be the best
way for small investors to take advantage.
Many commentators are confident that the smaller companies revival will
occur in 1993. Mind you, they said that about 1992 as well.
</TEXT>
