<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Financial Times Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (28):
Four new funds will seek to offer stability - Unit Trusts / Futures and
options will be used to reduce the risk. But will the average investor find
it easy to understand what they actually do?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN and BARBARA ELLIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REDUCING THE risk of equity investment may prove one of the themes of the
1990s.
Guaranteed funds (discussed on page 11 of this Review) are one approach, but
an alternative was launched by Fidelity - a futures and options fund.
Futures and options have a rather racy reputation, but they are frequently
used to reduce risk. In effect, they can be a form of insurance against a
sharp fall in a particular market.
That is the aim of four new 'stabiliser growth' unit trusts from Fidelity,
based on the UK, American, European and Japanese markets. An investor's
money will not rise as fast as the index in a bull market, but it will not
fall as quickly in a bear market. The minimum investment is Pounds 1,000,
with an initial charge of 5.25 per cent and an annual charge of 1.5 per
cent.
But the marketing flaw in these products is that the investor does not know
what his 'maximum loss' will be. If the market fell 50 per cent, Fidelity's
fund might fall, say, 15 per cent, and that is a risk that many cautious
investors will not accept. Nor will the average investor find it easy to
understand what a futures and options fund actually does.
So although these funds are more tax efficient than many guaranteed funds,
it is hard to see them taking off in the UK. Fidelity may have to prove the
concept through years of successful operation.
THE INCOME FACTOR
LOWER INTEREST rates and the unpredictability of investment returns have led
to a greater emphasis on income among managers currently launching
investment vehicles.
M &amp; G says its Managed Income Trust is aimed at the large number of people
who have difficulty with their choice of unit trust. Designed as a fund of
funds, to invest in the range of M &amp; G unit trusts, the Managed Income Trust
will hold a varying proportion of its portfolio in fixed-interest securities
and gilts, up to a maximum of 40 per cent.
Fund manager Chris Whitaker , who joined M &amp; G from County NatWest in 1991,
said the initial breakdown of investments would be around 20 per cent in
fixed interest securities, predominantly gilts, with a small proportion of
cash: possibly 5 per cent either directly in cash or in the M &amp; G Treasury
fund launched this month (see below).
About 55 per cent of the fund would be spread across the group's UK unit
trusts, with the balance going into a basket of funds invested in Europe,
the Far East and internationally.
Recognising that market movements before February might make a change of
strategy necessary, Mr Whitaker said M &amp; G saw the UK market as still having
some upside, though the pre-Christmas run-up in the market seemed to have
removed some of the potential for a traditional new year rally.
M &amp; G's Managed Income Trust will pay monthly income, at an estimated rate
of about 5 per cent gross annually if the fund is held via a personal equity
plan. Charges will be an initial 4.5 per cent and an annual 1.5 per cent,
with no additional charges on the unit trusts held by the fund.
The trust will be available at a fixed price of 25p per unit during the
launch period, which runs from February 6 to February 26, and the minimum
investment will be either Pounds 1,000 or Pounds 50 a month.
FUND WITH A CHEQUEBOOK
UNIT TRUSTS are showing further signs of adapting to an era in which
investors are looking for alternatives to the building society.
M&amp;G's new Treasury fund, by investing in UK Treasury bills and other
money-market instruments, aims to offer a yield higher than that obtainable
from most building society instant access accounts. Income will be payable
monthly, and investors will be given a chequebook, allowing them to transfer
funds (subject to a minimum of Pounds 250) into a bank or building society
account.
There is no initial charge, but an annual fee of 0.6 per cent; the minimum
investment is Pounds 5,000.
Such funds are relatively commonplace in the US; and, indeed, the most
obvious competitor in the UK is the cash account operated by the US group
Fidelity.
Money market funds are never likely to offer the best possible rate in the
market, but are sure to provide a rate which is highly competitive.
In contrast, some building society accounts offer a top-of-the-range
interest rate to attract investors, only to lower rates to below-market
levels after a year or so. All too often, inertia (or ignorance about the
rate change) stops investors from moving their money at the right time.
Eventually, such funds may offer the ability to make standing orders and
even cashpoint withdrawals. But, although the Fidelity fund has now topped
Pounds 100m, UK money market funds are simply not yet big enough to make
such services profitable at the low level of fees charged.
AN EASIER ROUTE INTO PIBS
PERMANENT INTEREST-bearing securities have many attractions for investors in
the current world of low rates. Pibs offer a high, fixed income and come
with the backing of building society names which most investors can
recognise.
The problem is that the market is illiquid, and some Pibs come in large
(Pounds 50,000) denominations. Holders of securities will rank well behind
depositors in the queue for repayment, should the society go bust.
So careful selection in this area is needed. This is where ExBal, a new unit
trust, claims it can help. It will invest around 60 per cent of its
portfolio in Pibs, with the remainder in the zero-coupon shares of
investment trusts to provide scope for capital growth.
The snag with this structure is that it sharply brings down the yield - the
main reason why private investors might be attracted to Pibs in the first
place. The initial yield on the trust was 6.5 per cent at launch, and that
had slipped to 6.3 per cent by mid-January.
The initial charge is 5.25 per cent and the annual charge 1 per cent. The
minimum investment is Pounds 750.
Exeter Fund Managers, who run the trust, are specialists in the
split-capital area.
GOLD LOSES ITS GLITTER
ALL THAT glitters has been distinctly unprofitable for unit trust investors
over the past five years. Of the 10 worst-performing trusts over the five
years to January 1, five were gold funds.
In the 1980s and early 1990s, gold has consistently failed to show the kind
of 'safe haven' characteristics that it showed in the 1970s. Even the Gulf
War failed to spark a rally. The price of bullion has been stuck between
Dollars 300 and Dollars 400 per ounce in the 1990s. Some disillusioned
central banks have recently offloaded part of their holdings.
With expectations for world inflation still low, it is hard to see what
could cause the gold price to rally. Which may be bad news for investors in
trusts such as Waverley Australasian Gold, which turned Pounds 100 into
Pounds 39.18 over five years.
Top-performing funds: pages 30 and 31
</TEXT>
<XX>
