<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Financial Times Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (3):
Don't let the years slip away - The Tax Deadline 2, Pensions / If you can
afford to pay more than the maximum contribution, you may still be able to
mop up unused past tax relief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBBIE HARRISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS THE tax year ends, retirement gets another year closer. The self-employed
and those employees who do not have access to a company pension scheme have
considerable flexibility in maximising tax relief, by making end-of-year
pension contributions to a personal pension plan or a retirement annuity
contract.
In particular, those who were unable to make contributions over the past few
years can take advantage of Inland Revenue rules that allow them to mop up
unused tax relief.
The amount you can pay into your plan will vary according to your age,
earnings and whether you have a personal pension, a retirement annuity or a
combination of the two.
Personal pensions replaced retirement annuities in 1988, but, although the
latter are no longer sold, it is still possible to make contributions to an
existing contract. If you contract out of the state earnings-related pension
scheme (Serps) using an 'appropriate' personal pension, then your Serps
rebate is paid in addition to your contribution limits.
Contributions are based on 'net relevant earnings' which, for the employed,
roughly equate to gross earnings, and for the self-employed are defined as
income chargeable under Schedule D (that is, income less capital allowances
and other allowable expenses).
Personal pension holders are further restricted by the 'earnings cap', which
limits the maximum salary on which personal pension contributions can be
based to Pounds 75,000 for the 1992-93 tax year. This means that a young
employee up to age 35 can pay a maximum personal pension contribution of
Pounds 13,125, while someone aged 62 can pay up to Pounds 30,000.
The earnings cap does not apply to contributions paid solely to retirement
annuities, although maximum contribution limits are lower under these
contracts than on personal pensions. If you want to pay contributions to
both types of plan, then the personal pension limits apply across the board
but you immediately become subject to the earnings cap.
Specialist help is needed if you are a high earner and want to find out
which plan you should pay into for the current tax year. Gerry Hart,
managing director of tax consultants RBA Associates, said that if your
earnings exceed the following figures you can put more into a retirement
annuity for 1992/93 than into a personal pension:
 ------------------------------------
Age at April 6 1992        Earnings
 ------------------------------------
Under 36              Pounds 75,000
36-45                        85,714
46-50                       107,142
51-55                       112,550
56-60                       116,667
61-74                       109,090
 ------------------------------------
Employees with personal pensions pay contributions net of basic rate tax,
and must claim higher-rate tax relief, where applicable, through their tax
return. Employees with a retirement annuity and the self-employed with
either contract, pay contributions gross and claim tax relief through their
annual return.
Most pensions advisers reckon the best way to structure contributions is
through single premium payments. This is because the amount deducted from
your contribution to cover the provider's management charges and the
intermediary's commission is far less on a single premium than on a regular
monthly or annual premium arrangement. This same advice applies to employees
who want to top up their company pensions through a free-standing additional
voluntary contribution.
Provident Life and Professional Life offer non-commission plans, while unit
trust personal pensions, available from Gartmore, Rothschild Asset
Management and Fidelity, pay commission at about 4 per cent. It is also
possible to have all or part of the commission on a standard life-office
plan reinvested in your fund, but this must be handled by an adviser and
naturally you will pay a fee in lieu of the commission given up.
MOPPING UP UNUSED RELIEF
If you have sufficient capital to pay more than the permitted maximum
contribution for the current year, then you can make use of the Inland
Revenue 'carry-back and carry-forward' provisions to mop up unused tax
relief in previous years.
Professional advice should always be sought, because the rules governing
these provisions are complex, particularly where you have a combination of
personal pension and retirement annuities.
Under the carry-forward provisions, if you had self-employed or
non-pensionable earnings in any of the previous six years and did not use up
the full contribution limit at the time, you can make use of that tax relief
now.
To calculate unused relief, simply deduct contributions paid from maximum
permissible contributions in relation to net relevant earnings for each tax
year.
Susan Smith, assistant product manager at Scottish Provident, said: 'There
are three important points here: First, maximum contributions must have been
paid in the current tax year before any carry-forward exercise can be used.
Second, you must work through each previous tax year in order, starting with
year six and working forward to the present. Third, in the year of
assessment, the contribution you want to pay must not exceed your net
relevant earnings for that year.'
Employers are not permitted to contribute to the 'mop up' exercise - they
can only contribute towards the current tax year's limits.
Carry-back provisions allow you to make an election for your contribution to
be treated as though it had been paid in the previous tax year. If you had
no earnings in the previous tax year, you may be able to carry the
contribution back to the year before that. Unlike the carry-forward
provisions, if you use carry-back, you do not have to make the maximum
contribution in the current tax year first.
Carry-back is particularly useful for those whose earnings fluctuate from
year to year. Authors and actors are classic examples, but many
self-employed people have this problem. If your earnings last year took you
into the 40 per cent tax bracket, but this year you are only liable to
basic-rate tax, through the use of carry-back you can treat your next
contribution as though it were paid in 1991-92 and claim the full 40 per
cent tax relief.
A request for contributions to be carried back must be made within three
months of the end of the current tax year to carry back to the 1992-93 tax
year.
Finally, a combination of the carry-back/carry-forward provisions can be
used to mop up tax relief for up to seven years. The timing of payments
under this arrangement is critical, and should only be attempted through a
pensions and tax expert.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6371  Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Taxes.
    CMMT  Comment and Analysis.
</TP>
