<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Financial Times Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (1):
Long-term investors prosper amid the rubble - Keynote / But many older ones,
seeking to live off their investment income, are having to tighten their
belts, as interest rates fall and the structure of returns changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE MAY not be another quarter like it for quite a while.
Under the impetus of two separate one-point cuts in short-term interest
rates, on October 16 and November 13, and of a further depreciation of
sterling from Dollars 1.78 to Dollars 1.51, the UK stock market showed
healthy gains, and in sterling terms the overseas stock and bond markets
showed up very positively, too.
Even government securities (or gilt-edged) weathered the conditions quite
well, although there were misgivings about a worsened outlook for inflation
and government borrowing. But while fixed-income gilts achieved only slight
gains, in doing so they consolidated their significant advances earlier in
the year.
During the October-December period the FT-SE 100 Index climbed 11.5 per cent
in capital value, and the FT-Actuaries World Index in sterling terms put on
17 per cent. In dollar terms, it is true, the World Index went down by about
1 per cent, but that was strictly a problem for the Americans.
It may have been a fool's paradise, but long-term UK investors continued to
prosper in 1992 amidst the rubble of Britain's economy, which appears to
have shrunk by about 1 per cent during the 12 months.
Fortunately, a certain amount of economic recovery began to be evident by
the end of the year. Car sales jumped in December, taking annual
registrations to just above the 1991 level, and although December retail
sales overall were unexciting, business generally seemed to improve markedly
over the Christmas and New Year period. Some of the business-confidence
indicators began to pick up, too, though there have been false dawns in this
respect before.
In terms of total return (capital gains plus gross income), UK equities
produced about 21 per cent and gilts 16 per cent during 1992. The best
results of all were generated by foreign currency bonds, which in many cases
returned 30 per cent or more to sterling investors, with Japanese and Dutch
government bonds leading the pack.
There was a harsh flipside to all this, however. Investors in short-term
savings accounts were exposed to the drop in interest rates, so that by the
end of the year the gross return on instant access building society accounts
had slipped to about 5 per cent. Older investors seeking to live off their
investment income found that they were having to tighten their belts, after
several fat years.
At the end of June long-dated gilts yielded almost 1 per cent less than the
clearing bank base rate. By the end of September they yielded 0.4 per cent
more. And by the end of December that positive differential had widened to
1.9 percentage points. It is an odds-on bet that the gap will grow further
in 1993.
These changes in the structure of investment returns (technically described
as a steepening of the yield curve) are having dramatic effects on savers
and on institutions. During the years of high interest rates from 1988 to
1991, the building societies were pulling in anywhere between Pounds 500m
and Pounds 1,000m a month in net receipts over their counters. But in the
final two quarters of 1992 that changed into a net outflow (although
interest credited to accounts kept the overall savings total growing on a
modest scale).
New savings are, in effect, now going elsewhere. Sales of unit trusts are
picking up, and the life assurance companies are doing a big business in
lump-sum savings products such as with-profits bonds and guaranteed income
bonds. National Savings will contribute Pounds 5bn or more to government
funding this financial year, against a negative figure in 1989-90, although
Norman Lamont withdrew the controversial First Option Bond (the particular
target of building-society fury) in his Autumn Statement on November 12.
The decline of the credit institutions has gone hand-in-hand with the
weakness of credit-based investments, notably property. Whereas the
sensitive and liquid equity market moved ahead in the fourth quarter of
1992, the sluggish and inefficient property markets carried on sinking. Both
the residential and commercial markets continue to be dominated by the
overhang of property for sale, and values typically fell by 8 to 10 per cent
during the year as a whole, though with substantial regional variations.
The average house price fell by anywhere between 2 and 5 per cent in
October-December, depending on whether you believe Halifax or Nationwide's
statistics. This failure of values to respond positively to the drop in
mortgage rates shows how deep-rooted are the problems of the owner-occupied
residential property market.
For instance, unemployment was rising by about 30,000 a month during the
final quarter. Headlines about redundancies everywhere from Barclays Bank
and British Coal to British Aerospace scarcely served to boost the
confidence of house-buyers. Perhaps the time has now come for
bargain-hunting in houses, but prices are unlikely to recovery for some time
yet.
So why did the UK stock market take such a different view? Partly because it
has an international dimension. UK-listed companies earn getting on for half
of their profits overseas, and devaluation will consequently help their
earnings as measured in pounds. But by December buyers were switching their
emphasis to the smaller, domestically-oriented companies which had been left
behind in the market's rally. These companies will need a revival in the
British economy to justify their higher ratings.
There were clearly also some purely financial reasons behind the strength of
share prices in late 1992. A lull in the pace of government funding
coincided with a virtual absence of issues by companies. As interest rates
fell, liquidity was drained out of the money markets and attracted into the
long-term markets. The balance was favourable for the stock market.
This may only have been temporary, however. The Bank of England will be
stepping up its sales of gilt-edged in 1993, seeking to hit a gross target
of Pounds 50bn or more. Because foreigners have mostly stopped buying gilts,
in view of the extra currency risks since the UK's exit from the European
exchange rate mechanism in September, the buying power of domestic investors
could be tested.
British companies will also be tempted to launch rights issues into a
buoyant stock market, especially if there is a glimmer of light visible in
the economy.
A crucial element will be the trend in dividend payments. Although October
to December is not a major season for dividend declarations, there were many
cuts, and by the end of the year aggregate payments were running slightly
below the 1991 level.
Last autumn, the stock market was busy celebrating the impending fruits of
devaluation. But in 1993 investors may be waiting anxiously for the harvest
to ripen.
</TEXT>
