<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lib Dems urge tax commitment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LIBERAL Democrats yesterday urged the government to say it would be
ready to see taxes rise in future and would temporarily increase public
borrowing to finance a job creation programme.
Mr Alan Beith, the party's Treasury spokesman, said such an announcement by
ministers would reassure the markets, and international investors in
particular, that they were serious about reducing the deficit, thus enabling
the government to borrow more.
Mr Beith, making a clear distinction between borrowing for current spending
and for investment, said that acting now to cut unemployment would mean
lower borrowing in future. He called on the government - as proof of its
financial rectitude - to drop its promise to cut the basic rate of income
tax to 20p.
The Liberal Democrats urged the government to adopt its 'Action for Jobs'
package in the Budget. Mr Beith doubted the effectiveness of short-term tax
incentives. In his experience business preferred to be confident about
stability.
The package of measures would amount to just under an extra Pounds 4bn in
borrowing, including projects such as a training programme (Pounds 750m) and
investment in housing (up to Pounds 1bn).
The party believes that its plans would mean that 350,000 fewer people would
be unemployed by April 1994.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, accused the government of
complacency and believing its own propaganda, and said that the 'dash for
growth' had petered out in the face of the recent rash of bad economic news.
The party's proposals also criticise the Labour idea of a 'windfall' tax on
the profits of privatised utilities, arguing that it could reduce
infrastructure projects and cost jobs.
