<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Building a new bonfire of inanities
 -Philip Stephens asks Neil Hamilton about the latest Tory crusade against
bureaucracy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN politicians cast around for newsworthy initiatives to slip into
otherwise dull speeches, they sooner or later alight on the idea of a drive
to cut red tape.
Lord Wilson, never one to miss a good headline, saw the potential as long
ago as 1948 when as president of the board of trade he lit a bonfire of
war-time controls. Successive prime ministers - Lady Thatcher among them -
have followed his example, promising (and sometimes delivering) to lighten
the grip of the state bureaucracy on the nation's wealth-producers. In the
meantime, their governments have gone on legislating and regulating.
Now it is Mr John Major's turn. Next Tuesday cabinet ministers and permanent
secretaries will be ushered into No 10 Downing Street to provide tinder for
the latest bonfire.
Mr Neil Hamilton, the minister at the Department of Trade and Industry
charged with de-regulation, has been appointed guardian of the pyre.
He is an eminently suitable choice. A rightwinger with a libertarian streak
and an instinctive contempt for the bureaucrats of Brussels, Mr Hamilton is
refreshingly candid about the risks.
He is ready to admit that after 14 years in power the government cannot
absolve itself of responsibility: 'This is an exercise in in self-criticism
if you like. Regulation grows like mould. Until recently we have not had a
system in place for evaluating the costs'.
There are no illusions about the strength of Whitehall inertia. 'Obviously
permanent secretaries are not going to be impressed by a pipsqueak
undersecretary like myself.'
But he is assured of Downing Street's backing. The purpose of the seminar is
'to stamp on this initiative the prime minister's personal commitment and to
require each department to produce results'.
He chooses a canine metaphor: 'The prime minister has appointed me his
personal rottweiler to charge up and down Whitehall yapping and biting
people.' He intends to enjoy the exercise.
The starting point is the 6,000-odd government regulations turned up by a
Whitehall census of red-tape. Many are necessary, but many others impose no
special burden on business. But Mr Hamilton is convinced that many others
are too complicated, and some totally unnecessary.
He admits that a good proportion - more than 1,000 - were issued by his own
department. Among those which he is keen to scrutinise closely are company
law - particularly the audit requirements for small companies - and the
rulebooks which govern the City's self-regulatory agencies.
The employment, social security, environment and agriculture departments and
the Home Office are among the other main targets across Whitehall. So too
are the Treasury's tax-collecting agencies. Planning rules, health and
safety requirements, environmental health regulations and consumer
protection measures will be rigorously examined.
Mr Hamilton cites recent Home Office draft fire regulations - with a price
tag for industry estimated variously at between Pounds 1.5bn and Pounds 7bn
 -as an example of the old culture.
Before it was caught in a new system designed to ensure a 'cost-compliance'
evaluation, the Home Office wanted entrepreneurs working from home to
reverse all doors and install illuminated fire-exit signs over each of them.
That was an example of over-implementation of decisions made in Brussels. Mr
Hamilton is engaged on a census of all EC regulations which Britain has
implemented since joining the community nearly 20 years ago. But he is
acutely aware that 'we normally find a 10-page EC directive becomes an
85-page statutory instrument'.
Then there is the knee-jerk response to well-publicised tragedies. Mr
Hamilton cites the reaction a few years ago to the salmonella-in-eggs scare
when it 'threatened to destroy an entire industry' with new hygiene rules.
In future the government - and the media - should make rational judgments on
the degree of safety sensible relative to the cost. Otherwise cars would be
banned from the roads to improve safety. Cabinet ministers have been given
until April to bring forward regulations which can be scrapped or
simplified.
Mr Hamilton expects to light his bonfire in the parliamentary session which
begins in October. He wants to import from the US the idea of 'sunset'
provisions in new regulations which provide for the automatic expiry of some
regulations unless they are re-introduced. Cost-compliance assessments
should also be the norm. Ministers should be ready to measure also the costs
against the risks - to the public and their own political careers.
Mr Hamilton sounds determined, a round peg in a round hole whose task
coincides with his instincts. Whether he will convince his colleagues is
another matter. He recently lost a Whitehall battle against a regulation
requiring manufacturers to fit plugs on electrical appliances. The new rule
will be enforced by the DTI.
</TEXT>
<XX>
