<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Parliament and Politics: Smith raps standards of government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN SMITH, the Labour leader, last night launched a scathing attack on
what he claimed were declining standards in government, warning that
unchecked they would 'corrode public confidence' in the political system.
In a strongly worded speech Mr Smith accused Mr John Major's administration
of 'arrogance and insensitivity' in its behaviour and of compromising the
traditional impartiality of civil servants.
Calling for a Freedom of Information Act and a code of conduct to oversee
the roles and responsibilities of civil servants and ministers, he argued
that the consequence of a single party holding power for 13 years had been
to expose serious weaknesses in the constitution.
The Labour leader went on to demand that parliament be given more powers
over the executive, that greater devolution be given to the nations and
regions, and the restoration of power and influence to local government.
Mr Smith's attack signals a determination by Labour to tap what it believes
is mounting public anger at cavalier behaviour by senior ministers and
systematic abuses of power.
His 10-page speech insisted that his office had been inundated with letters
from the public expressing anger at efforts by the prime minister to brush
aside criticism.
He went on to single out as an example Mr Major's refusal to answer his
questions on the payment by the Treasury of some of Mr Norman Lamont's legal
fees over the eviction of a tenant from his London home.
'Hard-working British people do not pay taxes in order that they should be
used to bail out a Tory minister from some wholly private embarrassment for
which he himself was responsible,' he said.
As other examples of what he viewed as unacceptable behaviour, he went on to
cite Mr Michael Heseltine's failure to consult on the pit closure programme
that was later judged illegal.
The Labour leader then turned his fire on Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign
secretary, whom he claimed had authorised British companies to pursue
telecommunications projects in Iraq at a time when the RAF was enforcing UN
sanctions against the country.
'This is a government from which nobody resigns unless absolutely forced to
do so by overwhelming pressure from the public, the media and their own
backbenchers,' he said, adding: 'Nobody takes responsibility.'
</TEXT>
