<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Call for improved road to pit areas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government was yesterday urged to build a dual carriageway through the
Peak District National Park between Sheffield and Manchester to ease the
problems of pit closures in South Yorkshire.
The call came from the Yorkshire and Humberside Partnership, which comprises
the region's offshoots of the Trades Union Congress and Confederation of
British Industry as well as 14 chambers of commerce, Yorkshire and
Humberside Development Association and the regional association of local
authorities.
The partnership wants the present A-road route over the Woodhead pass
upgraded to a dual carriageway.
Such a fast, all-weather road - dual-carriageways are more easily cleared of
snow - would improve access between the coalfield closure areas and
Manchester Airport, boosting prospects for inward investment and easing
congestion on the trans-Pennine M62.
Present direct routes between Sheffield and Manchester are
single-carriageway A roads over the Woodhead or Snake passes, both of which
are often closed by snow.
The cities are less than 40 miles apart but the journey can sometimes take
up to two hours at peak periods, making it slightly quicker to travel twice
the mileage using the M62 and M1.
</TEXT>
