<DATE>930129
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Obituary of Lord Poole: Senior Tory and ex-FT chairman
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD POOLE, who died yesterday aged 81, straddled the worlds of finance and
politics. He played a key role in the organisation of the Conservative party
during the 1950s and 1960s. At the same time, as the closest adviser to Lord
Cowdray, he was deeply involved in directing the affairs of what was, until
publicly floated, one of the largest privately owned business empires in the
country, the S. Pearson group. As chairman of Lazards, he was for many years
a central figure in the City.
Oliver Poole was born on August 11 1911 and was educated at Eton and Christ
Church, Oxford. After a brief period in the Life Guards he joined a firm of
building contractors in Birmingham, where in the difficult trading
conditions of the mid-1930s he acquired his first direct experience of
financial management. Shortly before the outbreak of war he joined his
family business - Lloyd's insurance broking.
During the war he served with the Eighth Army in north Africa, where he
helped to plan the landings on Sicily and later did the same with 21st Army
Group for the D-Day landings. He was mentioned in dispatches three times and
was awarded many decorations. At the end of the war he was Colonel (Q Plans)
to Field-Marshal Montgomery.
His organisational skills drew him to the attention of the Tory party.
Towards the end of the war, Conservative Central Office asked him to stand
as a candidate and he entered the Commons in 1945 as MP for Oswestry. But he
did not find the life of an MP congenial and quickly decided not to stand at
the next election.
His subsequent backstage role was crucial to the party. Poole had already
had a hand in the pamphlet The Right Road for Britain, which became the
basis of the 1950 election manifesto. In May 1950 he became political head
of the Conservative Political Centre in succession to RA Butler. His
interest in business advanced simultaneously: shortly before leaving the
Commons in 1950 he was asked by Lord Cowdray to join him in running S.
Pearson. The pair had become friends at Oxford, both being members of the
University polo team.
At that time the S. Pearson group faced the problem of adjusting to some
drastic changes which had recently affected its interests. The main aviation
activities had been nationalised, as had been the coalmines and the
electricity utilities. What was left was an assortment of businesses, most
of them sound and profitable but needing to be co-ordinated on a more
rational basis.
Poole helped to formulate a new strategy for the company, selling off some
of the peripheral interests and concentrating on four main lines of
development - banking and finance, publishing, the industrial group centred
on Doulton, and oil. His main personal interest lay on the banking side, and
he was particularly concerned to develop close co-operation between the
three Lazard companies in London, Paris and New York. During the 1960s, he
was credited with instilling a new verve into Lazard's activities in London.
Poole also took an active interest in other parts of the group. He played a
central role S. Pearson's decision to acquire control of the Financial Times
in 1957 and he became chairman of the paper in October 1958 on the death of
Viscount Bracken. He held the post until the end of 1960, when he was
succeeded by Lord Robbins.
He continued to be very much an international figure and in 1972 became a
member of the main Fiat Board. Politics, however, had remained an important
part of his life. In 1952 he was appointed joint treasurer of the
Conservative Party, a post in which his administrative talents, his
profusion of new ideas and his ability to raise very large sums of money
brought him increasingly to the attention of the party's hierarchy.
Poole succeeded Lord Woolton as party chairman in 1955, a post perfectly
suited to his taste for working in the background. He travelled round the
constituencies and forged close ties with Central Office, which were to
serve as the basis for a decade of Conservative party organisation. Poole
was created a baron in 1958 and a Privy Counsellor in 1963.
In 1957 the job of chairman was divided, functionally, between Poole and
Lord Hailsham - Poole quietly working away on improving the efficiency of
the party machine while Lord Hailsham stumped the country making rousing
party speeches.
'Leaving the limelight to others,' Mr Michael Foot wrote later, 'Lord Poole
created the most efficient machine which has ever contested an election in
this country. He knew more about the details in every marginal constituency
than had ever been assembled at a party headquarters before.'
At the end of that period Poole returned to the City, but in 1963 he was
suddenly recalled by Harold Macmillan to serve as joint chairman with Iain
Macleod in the aftermath of the Profumo scandal, when Macmillan's leadership
of the party was under siege. He served in this post for just over a year.
He was known to his closest friends for his great kindness and generosity to
those of other political persuasions. 'He could never stand rancorous
politics,' said one. 'He accomplished great good and kindnesses by stealth.'
</TEXT>
