FT  29 JAN 93 / Medal bike on track for road
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DESIGN elements from the Lotus Engineering bicycle on which Chris Boardman
won an Olympic gold last year are to be used by Leeds-based cycle and
clothing group Casket to make a range of bicycles under licence.
Casket, which claims more than 20 per cent of the UK cycle market through
its British Eagle, Claud Butler, Falcon and Townsend brands, will make and
distribute the cycles under the LotusSport brand through its British Eagle
arm.
The licensing agreement is with Lotus Engineering, the consultancy arm of
Group Lotus, the Norfolk-based sports-carmaker.
British Eagle will make the cycles to Lotus designs incorporating the basic
concept of a one-piece moulded frame.
The machines, expected to be launched in the UK during March, will sell for
between Pounds 500 and Pounds 1,100.
