<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: Zinc and lead prices rise on
Australian group's output cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ZINC PRICES jumped by more than 5 per cent when trading started in London
yesterday after Pasminco, the Australian natural resources group, said
market conditions were forcing it to restructure its loss-making zinc and
lead mining operations at Broken Hill, with the loss of 500 jobs.
Lead prices also moved up as analysts calculated that the restructuring
would remove roughly 25,000 tonnes a year of zinc and about 32,600 tonnes of
lead from the market.
Some analysts suggested, however, that the higher prices would be
short-lived unless other producers followed Pasminco's example.
Mr William Adams, analyst at Rudolf Wolff, part of the Noranda natural
resources group, said: 'It is rather surprising that this news has had such
an effect. I would expect selling to come in when the market has
reconsidered.' He suggested the higher price levels would not be sustained
'unless there are more cuts and the market is certainly nervous about this
possibility.'
Mr Nick Moore, analyst at Ord Minnett, a subsidiary of the Westpac banking
group, pointed out, however, that, although Pasminco's production cuts did
not look very substantial when compared with zinc stocks of nearly 1m tonnes
or lead stocks of about 640,000 tonnes, they would have an important impact
on market supply and demand this year.
He calculated that, if nothing else changed, the expected statistical supply
deficit in the zinc market this year would increase from 50,000 to 82,000
tonnes while 'at one stroke the lead supply surplus is eradicated.' Mr Moore
said that 'at today's prices' more zinc production cuts must be expected.
On the London Metal Exchange zinc for delivery in three months reached
Dollars 1,127 a tonne in early trading, an eight-week peak, before closing
at Dollars 1,115.25, up Dollars 40.75. Three-month lead closed up Pounds
7.375 a tonne at Pounds 295.50.
Pasminco said its Broken Hill operations were too inefficient to operate
profitably at current low world prices for lead and zinc, in spite of
capital investment of ADollars 304m since 1988.
It said the northern operations, previously scheduled to close in 1995,
would shut immediately because of mounting losses and the poor economic
outlook in Australia and other developed countries. The remaining southern
operations were to be restructured to increase production to 3,000 tonnes of
ore a year from each employee, from about 1,500 tonnes a year.
This would boost production at the southern operations to 2.4m tonnes a year
compared with current production of about 2.6m tonnes from the combined
operations.
Asset write-downs, redundancy payments and restructuring were expected to
cost about ADollars 40m before tax. Pasminco said in October that it
expected to return to profitability in the year to June, following two years
of heavy losses.
</TEXT>
