<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / G7 nuclear safety accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING industrial nations, fearing another Chernobyl-style nuclear
disaster, have finalised plans for a Dollars 700m (Pounds 452m) fund to
improve safety at east European reactors, officials said yesterday, Reuter
reports from Bonn.
Officials who took part in nearly six months of German-led talks by experts
from the Group of Seven leading industrial states said the group had finally
agreed on rules for the fund on Wednesday.
They said swift approval by G7 governments was expected for the fund, to be
administered by the London-based European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development, which specialises in helping Europe's former communist states.
Other industrial countries were expected to join the G7 states - the US,
Japan, Canada, Germany, France, Britain and Italy - with contributions to
the so-called 'nuclear safety account'.
The fund will finance loans to east European governments for upgrading
operations and hardware in projects that cannot be covered by bilateral aid.
The safety improvements are meant for some of 32 Soviet-built reactors
deemed safe enough to be worth upgrading, but another 26 reactors, most of
them of the Chernobyl type, will be excluded.
</TEXT>
