<PROFILE>_AN-DA3AKAC4FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930129
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / International Company News: Nortel chief goes in 'orderly
transition'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DR PAUL Stern is stepping down as chief executive officer of Northern
Telecom, just two days after the Canadian telecommunications equipment maker
unveiled unexpectedly strong 1992 earnings.
The company stressed yesterday that the initiative came from Dr Stern and
did not fit the pattern set by the string of executives who have been forced
from the top jobs of troubled North American companies. A spokesman said
that the move marked 'an orderly transition of a financially-strong
company'.
With a background in the telecommunications and computer industries, Dr
Stern's name is bound to surface as a potential candidate to replace Mr John
Akers as chief executive of IBM. Mr Akers announced earlier this week that
he would be stepping down once the computer giant has chosen a successor.
Prior to joining Nortel, Dr Stern held a senior position at Unisys, the US
computer group.
Despite Nortel's strong financial performance, signs of tensions in the
executive suite surfaced last year when Mr Jean Monty, head of its sister
company, Bell Canada, was named president and chief operating officer. The
move has been widely interpreted as an effort by BCE, the Montreal-based
conglomerate which owns 53 per cent of Nortel, to rein in Dr Stern.
Mr Monty will take over as Nortel's chief executive on March 1. Dr Stern
will remain as non-executive chairman. He will also become a visiting
professor at the Wharton business school and pursue other unspecified
interests.
Known for his strong-willed and opinionated management style, Dr Stern, aged
54, spearheaded a strategy to expand Nortel's business outside North
America.
Northern reported 1992 earnings of USDollars 536m, up from Dollars 497m in
1991.
See Management page
</TEXT>
