FT  29 JAN 93 / International Company News: 'Big Book' printer cuts jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
R. R. DONNELLEY, the world's largest commercial printer, announced that it
would take a Dollars 60m restructuring charge in the first quarter as a
result of the decision by retailer Sears, Roebuck decision to discontinue
its catalogue operations.
The Chicago-based printer had produced the Sears 'Big Book' for 80 years. It
said the charge would be taken primarily to cover the costs of shutting down
the Chicago printing plant that had produced the catalogue. The company said
660 full-time jobs would be cut.
Donnelley also reported record earnings for 1992 and the fourth quarter.
Fourth-quarter earnings were Dollars 73.1m (47 cents a share), up from
Dollars 68.5m (44 cents) a year earlier. For the year, Donnelley reported
earnings of Dollars 234.7m (Dollars 1.51), up from Dollars 205m (Dollars
1.32).
