<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JAN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Night owls will want to catch part two of Heimat (BBC 2, 11.20), the
remarkable German saga of small-town life which tonight has Hitler's rise to
power as its backdrop.
Friday night is meant to provide the kind of high-octane green fuel which
will take you on Saturday morning roaring into the garden, to dig and weed
and prune like a wild thing. The relative newcomer of the evening's
gardening fare is Gardens Without Borders (C4, 9.00). A minibus full of
gardeners and would-be gardeners tours France, led by an over-talkative
garden designer with questionable taste. Last week, passing through
Brittany, the pilgrims came to the manor-house and garden of a certain
Prince Peter Wolkonski. It was a place of such ravishing beauty that to see
it so fleetingly was something like a televisual experience of Le Grand
Meaulnes. But even the most perfect gardens can be marred by the combination
of a presenter's ego-mania, a garrulous and at times plain moronic
commentary, not to mention lamentably uninformative filming of the plants.
Thus far, the programme is a (French) dog's dinner.
</TEXT>
